In 2020 we were sent home from tour. I did something I had always wanted to do; start teaching online drum lessons.  I’m not going to say it was accidental but I didn’t intend to start the drumming community it turned into today called Matt Greiner Lessons (or MGL) and I have to say, it’s the best part of having my drumming website.  I’ve met many drummers I now consider my friends.  We’ve been doing Drummer Hangouts almost every week with few exceptions since June 2020.  We laugh, encourage each other, and learn from one another. It is pretty wild if you think about it. Those people on a Zoom screen would go on to become more than just a name and a face but friends who I look forward to seeing and hearing from each week.

Well, it breaks my heart that we lost a wonderful person this year who was an active part of MGL and a student of mine for years. A young girl who had become a good friend of many of ours.  Last year at CBR we all took a picture after the show in the Marriott, she was smiling ear to ear.  Little did we know it would be the last time we were all together with her. After Christmas Burns Red Night #2 I mentioned to a few drummers that were friends with her that we should go to the same place in the venue and take a picture.  We walked past the barricade, away from the stage, and over to the spot and I turned around to find 2x as many people as were in the original picture.

I am honored to know these people.  Honestly, I can’t even name everyone in the photo but I’m humbled to be part of something so great.

Thanks for reading and thank you to everyone who came to CBR this year and supported us.  And thank you to those who are active Members on mattgreinerlessons.com

I used to love watching Mike Portnoy’s drum solos, creativity off the charts! Isn’t it cool that as drummers we get to write our style into our sound? That’s one of my favorite things about having a cymbal with Zildjian, knowing that the Blast Bell is being played by drummers all over who are making it a part of their setup and their sound. 

Slide 3 is an order I shipped out 3 weeks to a drummer in Europe named Fabian. He messaged me last week to say he received it and is stoked! 

I’m doing “the Greiner” dance because 2022 has been a year to remember. Thank you to all who have picked up a Blast Bell, I hope it serves you well in finding your sound 🔔
Ringing in the New Year with some breakdown cheer 🔔🤘Wishing you a great start to 2023!

2022, the year we laughed all alone in that beautiful room. 

One last dance before walking out into the world for the very first time.  One last dance before starting our lives, together.

Happy New Year (a little late) to all of you.  I hope it’s a good year for you. A year of growth, a year that makes you proud of how you handled the ups and the downs and all the mundane moments in between.

As for me, I promise to love you @anniejgreiner 

I promise to help you, to listen, and to cheer you on.  Our days together will be years of living the life I’ve wanted for so long.

Happy New Year! 2023 WOOOHOOOO!

Longwood Gardens is incredible! @anniejgreiner and I love going every year and we seem to find something new each time we’re there. 

My favorite part of the gardens this year was the bell tower in Chimes Tower District.  Huge 100 year old Oak trees and a beautiful 50 foot waterfall next to a bell tower. Wow!

Thank you to our friends Corby and Jen for the awesome trip!
Having a great time at the PA Farm Show with @anniejgreiner. Can’t wait for the rodeo tonight!

I am very excited to announce a new drum course I just launched today called Tour Prep! 

A series of August Burns Red songs I rehearsed and recorded from overhead for this past 2022 Euro Tour! 

-  mattgreinerlessons.com or link in bio to sign up
- Click on Tour Prep to access the course
- My 3 goals in launching this course are:

Observe - I like to watch drummers playing just to see their gear, how they move around the kit, and to get new ideas of how to setup my kit. This course gives you the chance to see what I play and how I setup my drums.

Implement - By watching me play through these 12 songs you’ll learn fills and grooves that maybe you’ve heard before but now have a visual to help you make progress. 

Practice - This is what practice looks like for me. My hope is that this course can encourage you to practice hard in your own time!

The 12 songs in the Tour Prep course are:

Back Burner
Beauty In Tragedy
Bloodletter
Chop Suey!
Composure 
Defender
Invisible Enemy
King Of Sorrow
Marianas Trench
Meddler
Ties That Bind
Vengeance

“Sput Does Metal”

That was the title of the scratch track @sputacular emailed me a few weeks before shooting Zildjian Live in January 2020.

We got hit by a snowstorm the week I got the track so I played it on repeat on my phone in the cab of my truck while snowplowing 18 hours straight overnight. 

This project was a highlight of not just my career but my life in general. 

Getting to work with some of the best musicians, seeing friends I don’t get to see too often like @aspears and putting together a project backed by Zildjian, it’s something I’ll always remember and feel so blessed I had the chance to do.

Meeting @ashsoan and @drummerslams and @jdbeckmusic and @sarah_drums and @gergoborlai and @stanton_moore and @dennischambersofficial was really incredible. 

Video 2 is behind the scenes of right before the click track counted down and we started making music!

A note to you reading this: work hard and treat those around you well.  The “work hard” portion is that I wasn’t born with a ton of natural ability but I loved drumming and practiced a lot.  The “treat those around you well” part speaks to the way friends like @aspears and @ashsoan treated me on this project.  I remember driving home in the band van from the airport thinking about how part of me was changed because of their character and humility on that trip.

Thanks for reading, have a great day

I remember seeing Underoath on main stage at Cornerstone 2006. I stood side stage and watched thousands of fans sing along as the band performed like it was the last show they’d ever play. I had goosebumps, I’ll never forget it. 

To think we have a new song out today featuring @wschamberlain is just amazing to me. Thank you Spencer for doing this with us. 

RECKONING is out now!

Teaching drum lessons on tour is going really well! I like hearing about how drummers got started playing, it reminds me of when I wrote a check for $850 for my first kit, a chrome wrapped Pearl Export. Big toms, single kick pedal, and me just trying to figure out limb independence. 

That was the year 2000. Now 23 years later I’m really honored I get to spend time with drummers all over the map, some are just starting and others have been playing for longer than I have. 

If you’re looking for drum lessons check out my drumming website to see a list of tour dates, I have the link in my bio. If we are playing near you and you are interested then awesome, it’s $60 for 1 hour and we get started around 3pm. 

If you’re looking for online lessons then it’s $10/month to be a member on my drumming website, lots of ABR song breakdowns and courses on there as well as weekly Drummer Hangouts. 

Thanks for supporting me, I’m really happy I get to do this and glad to help if I can 🥁

Two things can be true at the same time; this tour is awesome and I miss you more than ever, Annie.

You love Jesus and follow your heart. I really love that about you.

You care about doing a good job and don’t need to be acknowledged for your work.

You are sweet and can always make me laugh even when you’re not trying to be funny, “I’m just saying” haha!

You are humble.

You are gorgeous.

And I love you, honey!

Miss you all the way from Texas,

Matt

A little taste of the 20 Year Anniversary drum solo!

Thank you @rayduker for the video 🤘
Thank you, Texas! So many tours, so many years, so many memories, and this was the biggest to date.

In 2010 I drove to Zildjian in hopes of making a darker sounding bell. I drove home with the bell I’ve used ever since! 

The Zildjian FX Blast Bell is in stores everywhere and I have 15 with me on tour. If you’re coming to a show and want one, please let me know. I’m happy to sign it and get it to you. 

Thank you to everyone who has supported me in the Blast Bell ride 🔔

This picture perfectly sums up the kind of person, pro photographer, and the kind of friend Ray has been to me for years. The man behind the camera putting the spotlight on everyone else. 

Happy Birthday, Ray! Today, you get the credit for more than a photo taken. You have been there to witness some of the biggest moments of my life (and have captured many of them on camera too haha!)

We’ve gone through some of our toughest times together as well. All in all, that’s what friends do and you’re someone I really am lucky to have, you’re like a brother to me. 

Let’s all wish @rayduker a happy birthday!

Our 20 year tour means a lot of different things to a lot of different people. It might be your first time seeing us or maybe you’ve been following since Thrill Seeker. No matter the reason you’re there, I am blown away every night playing drums on stage looking out at rooms full of people singing, moshing, (and my personal favorite) air drumming along. 

What a weekend in the Pacific Northwest. I like these pictures a lot:

1. Drum solo @giloscope 

2. Jon Dunn, formerly A&R rep at Solidstate, signed us and sent us to the studio to record Thrill Seeker with Adam D in Franklin, TN. in 2005 @rayduker 

3. ABR with Jon Dunn and Brandon Ebel (owner Tooth & Nail/Solidstate Records 

4. Shoutout to Josh, our tour manager who has been with us since the beginning @rayduker 

5. Stoked to have our friend and talented photographer  @giloscope with us for a stretch of tour 

6. Carlos (lighting designer) and Chris (audio engineer) working their magic 

7. Sold a @blastbell to a drum student in Portland!

8. Met up with my friend Chelsea, one of the sweetest and  most inspiring people I know

9. My favorite picture in the group, a screenshot of me FaceTiming with @anniejgreiner who is in Ireland and I miss very much. Annie found the stone monument in Galway City, Ireland and I tried to find the stone in Seattle that points directly through the planet to where she is. I never found the stone in Seattle but it was honestly the best part of the day (sold out show included) catching up on FaceTime.  I love you, Annie, you’re amazing and gorgeous and I can’t wait to see you again in 9 days!
Breakdowns and blast beats and the best times with the boys. 📸 @rayduker

Holy Ghost Notes. We recorded the 96th episode for my podcast last night. The wild thing is that we recorded it in the same Colorado town I got the phone call to start a podcast about drums and God in the first place. 

Thank you @timsonofander and everyone in the Inner Circle who has kept our conversations alive. 

If you haven’t listened to Holy Ghost Notes yet check it out everywhere podcasts are available. Thank you!
Wow. I don’t usually take my phone out on stage with me but I wanted my wife to see what we saw last night. This is post drum-solo when we get a picture with the crowd. Thank you, Denver. Unreal!

Greiner Farms hats are back on the bus! Message me to get yours as we wrap up tour in Little Rock, Nashville, or Charlotte. 

We are down to 25 because @dustindavidsonabr gets first dibs!

Also available on my drumming website via link in bio for $30. I’ll ship after I get home next week. 

Now to finish up this 20 year tour strong as we head east.

I started my drumming website after we got sent home from the Killswitch Engage tour March of 2020. 

It was finally happening!

I had always wanted to have a subscription based website where I could feature drumming content and courses. August Burns Red song breakdowns, groove and fill courses, 1 on 1 drum lessons; 2020 was the perfect time to put it all together. 

I launched mattgreinerlessons.com and a dream of mine came true. 

What I didn’t realize is that the connection with drummers would fall between the cracks with so many signing up for the site instead of doing 1 on 1 Zoom lessons with me. 

And that is when Drummer Hangout was born. We’ve been meeting weekly since summer of 2020 and it’s one of my favorite parts of MGL. 

Last week we talked about doing a good job regardless of how insignificant your role may seem. It all matters, every single thing and every single day. 

Grateful for 20 years with @augustburnsred 🤘

First leg of our 20 Year tour is over and it was terrific! 

21 shows down and now we’re home for a 3 week break. 

25 to go when the second leg of the tour resumes!

Thank you to everyone who came out and made this the best (half) tour I’ve ever done. 

It was challenging, it was tiring, but it was unreal and I’ll never, ever forget it. 

Thank you to the boys for making the last night in Charlotte special with some drum solo antics and pranks 🥁

📸 @jbburnsred

An important point to preach, a challenging word to hear, and such a great message for me to work on personally.  I hope it is helpful for you as well today wherever you are 🙏

I’m in a movie 🤩🥁

SPINNING GOLD 

It was an amazing opportunity for me to be part of this project. I got the call to portray Peter Criss of KISS. Big shoes to fill!

We drove up to NYC this week for the screening. Really proud of it and excited for the world to see it this Friday!

Spinning Gold is out in theaters today!

When I got the call to do this movie I was told that a good drummer who was willing to wear makeup and a wig was needed.  I joked in response, “like KISS makeup?” I’ll never forget hearing Mr. Bogart on the other end say, “actually, yes! You are Peter Criss, the drummer of KISS in a movie we’re making about my dad and Casablanca Records.”

It was amazing meeting my 3 band members on set and playing KISS songs together.  Go see Spinning Gold in theaters today🤘

Great interaction towards the end of my latest interview with @matthewgreiner of @augustburnsred. 🔗 to the entire interview is in the show notes or you can find it anywhere you get your podcasts.
🤘🤘
#undauntedlife #abr #deathbelow #augustburnsred #metalhead #marriage

Thank you and don’t give up 🥁 

I got cut off mid sentence. I guess I just had too much to say about you and about drumming. 

Can’t wait to get back on stage next week with the @augustburnsred boys and do more drum lessons on tour. I still have availability, link in bio to sign up!
Dirt in my boots

I always imagined that building a drum studio would be rewarding and it certainly has been. It’s nice having a place to practice, record drum ideas, and teach pro Zoom lessons.  But what I couldn’t have imagined is the community that we’ve built at mattgreinerlessons.com and I owe all of that to YOU drummers who get on Drummer Hangout every week and are learning drums on the site.  Thank you.

And if you’re reading this and have a goal in mind to do something my advice would be to just start.  Don’t wait. Don’t make excuses.  Don’t waste time.  Make a plan and get the job done.  If you fail then you know you tried.  And if you succeed then you might be writing a caption like this one day about how glad you are that you did what you set out to do.

2020 was the year I built my drum studio and started my drum lesson website. It’s 3 years later almost to the day that I finished the project and I realized this week that I never posted progress pictures from when it all came together.

It also dawned on me that I never thanked @mikeslessons for the advice he gave me on the phone.  Thanks, Mike!  I owe you for the cymbal shadow box idea and for helping me dial in my idea for my drum lesson website.
Gorgeous

Blast Bell in Times Square! 

Thank you to everyone who came out to see us in NYC last night. That show ruled!

In 2010 I drove to Zildjian headquarters in Norwell, MA. in search of a better sounding bell. I drove home with 7” and 9” bells that sounded awesome. 

13 years later and the 7” bell is now sold worldwide and known as the Blast Bell!

Stoked to play this bad boy every night and I’m grateful to @zildjiancompany and all of you for helping me get it into music stores and online around the world and onto your kit!

📸 @rayduker

I’m sitting on the bus looking at these pictures of us from 20 years ago and I’m thinking to myself, “how did 5 small town kids manage to start something that would go on to circle the globe for two decades? 

Even more, how did we find each other at the right time in the right place and build something that we’d be celebrating on an anniversary run 2 decades later? 

Tonight I’m thinking of 20 years ago to the day when we played our very first show as a band at Mastersonville Firehall. And I am very grateful. 

From my friend who knocked out the electricity to the show during This Day Forward’s set, to the town of Mastersonville never allowing shows again in the firehall because we put 300 too many people in there. It’s all part of this band’s beginning that has brought us here. 

All the memories are part of our DNA. All the shows are the building blocks that brought us to Detroit tonight where we played show 2,130. All the work is worth it. All the practice pays off. And All of YOU are the reason we still get to do this.

Thank you 🤘

I woke up to an email this morning from a drum student I was supposed to teach today. He said he was having some issues and couldn’t make the lesson.  He asked me to gift his 2 drum lesson spots to someone who might want them. 

3:30pm rolled around and I went to the front of the venue to get my 3 students for the day. There was a gentleman standing there who was waiting for the show. I asked if he’d like to come in for a drum lesson, that his spot was paid for. He said, “my son is in the car, he’d love that!”

The first picture you see is that man watching his son play drums. What I didn’t know at the time is that it’s his first time ever playing drums. He played an 1/8th note groove that impressed all of us there but none so much as his dad. His dad said, “I can’t believe this. I guess I’m buying a drumset now!”

Those 2 spots were paid for by a man who wanted to pay it forward. 

Nothing better on tour than getting a chance to teach drum lessons. Today was really special 🤘🥁
Matt gets “Jaked” during his drum solo.

20 Year Tour is going very well! Time for a day off with the only person who thinks my jokes are even remotely funny haha!

Annie, you’re just that sweet. I need to brag on you and say I am proud of you for working so hard while I’m away and for being the kind of friend you are to so many people. 

To the walks, the FaceTime chats (after you get your nails done and can’t wait to show me), the awesome friends you have, and the dinners we get to have together at our go-to Olive Garden. 

I love being together even when we are apart and I’ll see you IN PERSON soon!

Teaching today in Pittsburgh and I have a few more slots still open for today and for the rest of the tour (link in bio to signup for $60/lesson). 

Teaching on our 20 Year Tour has been awesome, I’ve absolutely loved it! 

Thank you to all the drummers out there who have taken lessons from me and to the teachers I’ve had in my life who have helped me become a better teacher, one in particular being @mikeslessons 🙏

Last week we played one of my favorite shows of the year in Minneapolis and then explored Chicago with @anniejgreiner

Day off today at home was awesome! 

8 shows to go on our 20 Year run and done 🤘

This day, 1 year ago, changed everything. 

Happy 1st Anniversary, @anniejgreiner 😍

You mean more to me every single day. 

You’re sweet, an incredibly hard worker, loyal, humble, honest, and absolutely gorgeous. 

I love you very much! Let’s celebrate 🎉

Thank you @jordanvoth for the amazing photos!

What a way to end it 🥁

Our 20 Year Tour ended Saturday night on a high note, one I won’t ever forget!

Two of the best drummers on the planet joined me on stage to play one final drum solo. 

What you don’t see is how Giuseppe and Ali asked me behind the drum riser before the solo if I was OK with them pranking me.  I said, “go ahead and go crazy.” G replied, “just stay true the course, we’ll fill in the gaps.”

Considerate, friends for life, and so insanely talented.

Come to think of it, that pretty much sums up everyone on the 20 year tour.

It’s bittersweet when you go home from a tour like that because a tour like that only happens once in 20 years.

Happy 14th birthday to Constellations!

I remember tracking drums like it was yesterday.

I had the hardest time tuning the 12” tom.  I actually got so frustrated @jason_suecof told me to throw the new head away and start over.  By the time we had drum tones and started tracking I remember being exhuasted from setup and tuning. 

We recorded in a great sounding, small studio in Orlando. I can’t remember the name but I remember the platinum and diamond Shania Twain albums on the wall.

The first song I tracked drums for was White Washed.  I used a 10” PDP snare drum with the snares off for the intro drum overdub.

We used what we called a “Frankenstein kit,” a combo of the best sounding drums we had at our fingertips.  Pearl Reference series 10” and 12” rack toms, Pearl Masters (I think?) 16” floor, 14” Steve Ferrone signature snare drum, and my 22” Truth bubinga kick.

I remember feeling bummed at first that I wasn’t using all @truthcustomdrums.  I changed my mind pretty quickly when I heard the drum tones in the control room.

This video was the first drum video we shot and uploaded to YouTube.  Thanks to Ronn Miller for the idea and taking the initiative to make it happen. It’s a snapshot in time that I’m really proud of and stoked to share. Thirty and Seven 🤘

This was the last full album we wrote in the chicken house at Greiner Farms.  I used to sharpie lyrics and breakdown patterns on the walls.  Crazy to see the finished product when it was all done. Jason Suecof helped us make an album that really helped solidify our career and future as a band. Thank you, Jason!

And thank you all for rocking out with us for 14 years of Constellations! I personally never get tired of playing songs off this album, I’m just glad I learned to not wear a hoodie with the hood up in the process.

I met a 13 year drummer in 2016 after teaching at Long Island Drum Center. He told me how much he liked drumming, how he was battling an illness, and then gave me a custom drum tool that he had designed. 

There are certain people you meet that you just don’t ever forget. 

It turns out I’d see this young man again years later when a friend sent me a drum video of some dude shredding on the kit. I realized that 13 year old kid had grown up and blown up online and his name is @greyson_nekrutman 

Makes you think about every person you meet along the way. You just never know. It makes me take my job seriously. Not just the drumming side of what I do but everything else. The people you meet, the places you go, the conversations you have. 

Greyson watched me play that night in Long Island. Last night I watched Greyson play for the first time. I couldn’t stop smiling and looking over at @mikeslessons 

“This kid is special. His singles are so fast. His style is so cool.” He headlined the UK Drum Show and he deserved every bit of the applause he got when he walked off.
 
He tells a story when he plays. The 2nd slide is a picture taken right after he played. The 3rd slide is from over 7 years ago right after I played. 

The last picture is the first person I want to thank for supporting me in leaving home to drum this weekend while having a 2-week old newborn at home. Getting off the train and seeing my girls made me so happy tonight. Thank you @anniejgreiner for everything, you are amazing and I love you more than ever. 

Thank you @theukdrumshow for putting together such an amazing event. 

Thank you @dwdrums for making it possible for me to be there. 

Thank you Mike for inviting me to teach in your Education Room. I had a blast!
I love my family so much.

Aaron Spears. I can’t believe you’re gone. I am so sorry for your family.

Aaron was kind of person who stopped rehearsing for his own performance at a Zildjian shoot to go watch another drummer play and make sure they had someone standing in their corner.

Aaron was the kind of person who sat in the back of the room watching with 100% heart and focus when someone else played drums and was the first to stand and start the applause when they were done. 

Aaron was the first to celebrate others success and the last to state his own.

Aaron was the kind of person who drove hours to support you on your big day.

Most importantly, Aaron talked about his wife and son like he was the luckiest man in the world to have them. 

Aaron, I’m going to really miss you.  You changed my life at Zildjian LIVE 2020 with the way I saw you treat everyone around you. Your humility lifted the world up. Your light won’t be forgotten. 20 year old me was listening to 3 drummers: Joe Walmer of Blind Influence, @davidhusvik of Extol, and @blakeyeatsteaky of BTBAM

I remember Blake teaching me a 6-stroke roll backstage in Greensboro in 2007

I remember watching White Walls intro drum part in Florida and thinking, “switching left foot between double pedal and hi hat, that is so sick!”

I remember finding out Blake leads double bass left foot like me and feeling less weird about it haha!

The drumming on Alaska and Colors taught me so much. 

I’m stoked to be friends.  A drumming influence for me in the industry for 20 years, ever since the Glass Casket days. 

And the coolest thing is seeing Blake prioritize family above all else.

Thanks for the influence and inspiration dude, appreciate you @blakeyeatsteaky

I was looking back at pictures of Aaron this morning. I remember when we made him a snare drum and delivered it to his house. That’s the day I played drums with him for the first time. 

It’s so funny because most of the time when we talked it had nothing to do with drums. Drumming is what connected us but his kindness and genuine love for everyone is what made us friends and kept us in touch for almost a decade.

I want to also say that I really appreciate you @sarahhagandrums for including me on so many projects with Aaron like Zildjian LIVE, Zildjian Inspirations, and the PASIC drum-off. Even the South-east Asia Zildjian clinic tour just a year after Aaron did it was your doing. 

This Christmas I’m thankful that I have the memories I do with the man Aaron Spears. I’m praying for those who are hurting and at a loss this holiday season. I’m sorry you’re going through setbacks and challenges and I hope and pray you can find peace and rest in the midst of it all.

Thank you, @aspears .  You left a legacy that I’ll always remember you by. You changed the way I live my life and I know that’s the case with so many others too. I miss you man!
Greiner Farms here!

Looking around my house this morning at all the ripped wrapping paper, opened gifts on the floor, and dishes in the sink it’s obvious that this was our first year as a family of 3 haha! 

We drank more coffee than we probably should have, cheered Annie on working 3 Christmas Eve services, lost at Holiday Jeopardy, and made Eleanor laugh as much as humanly possible. @jakeluhrsabr in Mariah Carey pose was celebrating with us all day long 🎄

Going into 2024 I am smiling as I write this just knowing that I met all of you in this picture because I started a metal band in my parent’s basement with my friends 20 years ago. 

A couple years ago we started the post-show picture tradition right after Christmas Burns Red. 

The practice leading up the shows is fun, the shows are a blast, but there was just something about taking this picture night 2 of CBR that sticks with me. 

We lost a friend recently who would’ve joined us for this picture. Most of this group of people knew her and loved her and that means the world to me to know we have such a tight knit community of fans who care.

Very thankful for all of you and hoping you have an awesome New Year!

My list of highlights for 2023 is summed up in that one simple smile. 

This is the year our family of 2 became 3. The year I became a dad and watched @anniejgreiner become a mom with more ease than I knew was possible.

The date was January 7th.  Annie made dinner and gave me a handwritten card with news that would change my life forever. Here’s what she wrote:

“With this New Year, 2023, I wanted to share a gift with you. In 2022 my name changed to Greiner, and in 2023 your name is changing to DAD!”

Looking at my little girl Eleanor content in her swing, woodstove fire keeping us warm, and Annie taking a nap before our New Years Eve get together, I am so thankful for the life we have. 

Happy New Year from my family to yours!

Nice working with you today, Collin. You have what it takes.

The X factor is work ethic. 

Build a routine.Your goals will naturally come to fruition.
